According to many SF critics, Smith's work was the epitome of &quot;primitive&quot; SF, with dizzying scale, terrific pace and energy, simple but sympathetic characterization, and little enough conventional literary value to send pompous high school English teachers into conniption fits. <br>
In particular, he is credited with the purest and most perfect evocation of the &quot;sense of wonder&quot;, so beloved of SF fans, in the form of the many shifts of scale in the Lensman series. <br>
<br>
My old friend (and near neighbor) Jack Williamson, still active at age 95, is a more sophisticated exponent of the &quot;Sense of Wonder&quot; and, indeed, brought it to the stage of requiring capitalization. <br>
<br>
Edward Elmer Smith (1890-1960) was called &quot;Doc&quot; because he was a legitimate Ph.D, in cereal chemistry. He spent most of his working life cooking up donut mixes, and many manufacturers still use his formulations.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 228<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 2:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Dunesberry RFD</span><hr size=1> Starring Ken Berry as Sam Atreides! (Yikes, I knew what you were talking about! Whats worse, my curiosity forced me to do some research – try this one <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.mayberry.com/tagsrwc/wbmutbb/startrek/index.htm" target="top">Mayberry in Star Trek</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> )<br>
<br>
Lots of good books to talk about. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Childhoods End</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – not really one of my favorites, but it is important which is why it was on my list. To depressing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Enders Game</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – Okay, but definitely not one of the greats.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>1984</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Brave New World</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> fall under what I call “Social Cautionary SF”, though I prefer <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Animal Farm</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to 1984. My favorite in this category (betraying my politics here) is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Atlas Shrugged</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – not an easy book to read and (judging from those I have debated about it with) impossible if you are philosophically opposed to Rand’s ideas (I agree with her more than I disagree). Many might say it isn’t SF, but it has hidden cities, indestructible metals, devastating sonic weapons, and near infinite power sources – what’s not SF?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Starship Troopers</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – Shame on me for I haven’t read the book, never got around to it. I was a bit disappointed in the movie; the whole point of the Mobile Infantry was the power armor which they just left out! I did like the scenes AC pointed out, and it isn’t a bad movie – just not one of the best.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Dune</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – Okay AC, stop using your mind probe on me! I managed to get through the first two books before I was done. The political backstabbing was tedious. Now I loved the 1985 movie, and I have seen it with both beginnings – I liked the original one better (the pseudo-animated one was ugly). Frank Herbert consulted on the movie, and they had his blessing on the changes they made (at least publicly). I hated the sonic guns, but loved the Spacers and their ships. BTW, someone stop his heirs from making more crappy books based on his crappy books please. <br>
<br>
E. E. “Doc” Smith created Space Opera. His characters may be simplistic, but depth and angst in a character isn’t required for the character to be realistic and enjoyable. Not all literature has to be Tolstoy. I didn’t realize he was a donut chemist! My respect for him just increased. SF guru and confectionary creator – Wow!<br>
<br>
Jack Williamson – <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Darker Than You Think</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is one of my favorite books! I love the fact that the main character and narrator is either insane or a serial killer. The sexy siren April Bell could be the poster girl for modern sex-based advertising! I bought the book, and I usually donate my books to the local library when I have finished them (I almost never re-read a book, semi-photographic memory and all); but a precious few I retain. This is one of them. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(6/28/03 11:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Rand's Book</span><hr size=1> <br>
Hey DrCarstairs, its interesting that you should mention <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Atlas Shrugged</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, because I spent two months out of last years summer reading that book. If I remember right its almost 1200 pages long. <br>
I found the book rather boring but I continued reading it just so that I could add it to my list of books read. I did skip the chapter called “this is John Galt speaking” because it is typical of Rand’s meandering writing style and I don’t think that I missed much by not reading it.<br>
Anyway, I find that I have more in common with Rand’s philosophy then today’s phony political “neo-cons” in other words “neo-conservatives” and other right-wing types that aren’t really for freedom as they are for their own agendas.   <br>
