The copyright date was 1949, rather than 1969.<br>
<br>
 <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://isfdb.tamu.edu/cgi-bin/p1.cgi?George_R._Stewart">Publication history at ISFDB</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?George_R._Stewart">George R. Stewart at ISFDB</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.lostbooks.org/reviews/1998-06-11-1.html">Review at Lost Books</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
This is easily one of the best &quot;end of the world&quot; novels; elegantly and convincingly written, with a wholly credible premise, a logical progression of events, and very subtle and believable characterization. In contrast to most of this sub-genre, it reaches some optimistic, even triumphant, conclusions about human nature, and nature in general <br>
I have seen many of its elements recycled, not to mention debased, in later works, especially Stephen King's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Stand</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, though Stewart's original lacks supernatural elements of any kind.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://isfdb.tamu.edu/">ISFDB (Internet Speculative Fiction Database)</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> is an exhaustively comprehensive resource on speculative fiction, with listings for virtually every person who has ever been published in fantasy, sci-fi and related fields. At least three members of this board are listed, including my humble self. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A> at: 6/28/03 10:12 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drcarstairs>DrCarstairs</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Utterly Mad Scientist</span><br>  Posts: 235<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/2/03 2:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=97.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/rant/AVitW/images/bioh.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Top 50 SF &amp; Fantasy Books</span><hr size=1> In honor of the Science Fiction Book Club's 50th Birthday they have compiled a list of the most significant Science Fiction and Fantasy books of the last fifty years, 1953 - 2002.<br>
<br>
1  The Lord of the Rings <br>
2  The Foundation Trilogy, Isaac Asimov <br>
3  Dune, Frank Herbert <br>
4  Stranger in a Strange Land, Robert A. Heinlein <br>
5  A Wizard of Earthsea, Ursula K. Le Guin <br>
6  Neuromancer, William Gibson <br>
7  Childhood's End, Arthur C. Clarke <br>
8  Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?, Philip K. Dick <br>
9  The Mists of Avalon, Marion Zimmer Bradley <br>
10 Fahrenheit 451, Ray Bradbury <br>
<br>
